2024 Update: Players can use cross-checks with their hands hip-width apart as long as they do not "STRIKE" the other player with the stick between their hands. When teaching players 1v1 Defense and Contact Rules, I like to use the phrase "Place and Push" to describe that they must place their stick on the opposing player and then push them away.

<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/msWSm877kaU?start=718&end=915&rel=0" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>
This section will cover the positions in the game of lacrosse.

The Set The set includes 3 sets of players that make up the 2-2-2. We will build from X to up top because that is how we will build the looks.

Group 1 - A2 and M3 at X.

Group 2 - A3 and M1 on the crease.

Group 3 - A1 and M2 up top.

The formation uses great spacing which creates difficult defensive decisions and simple offensive reads

The Play - The play consists of 3 actions.

Group 1 will run a 2 Man Game at X.

Group 2 will run a scissor cut motion.

Group 3 will snipers hunt skip lanes.

Group 1 - 2 Man Game at X Dodge to Score
The most important aspect of the 2 Man Game at X is that the ball carrier dodges to score. The set will create space on which ever side of the goal the dodger goes to. so they will have space to operate if they dodge high up the wing. If the ball carrier can beat their man, they will score or they will draw a slide. The cascade of looks are built upon the ball carrier beating their man.
Bring 2 to X
The 2 Man Game at X is predicated more on the ball carriers ability to beat their man on a dodge than it is to utilize the pick and roll to score. Although it uses a variety of 2 Man Game tactics (big little picks, swing picks, and mirrors) the main reason they run 2 Man Games behind is because it brings a second defensive player behind the goal so that drawing a slide will create a 4v3 up top as opposed to a 5v4.
Short Stick Defenseman
The majority of 2 Man Games at X will involve one or two short stick defenseman. We will attack the short stick defenseman by using inverts or big/little picks
Inverts - An invert is where we will pull a short stick defenseman behind the goal and dodging against them. In this case, the second player will mirror from the crease.
Big / Little Picks - A big little pick refers to the defensive players involved in the pick (Big = Long Stick, Little = Short Stick). In most circumstances, the long sticks will be defending our best offensive players and if we can generate a switch that puts a short stick on our best offensive player, we will have an advantage dodging to the goal.
The Eyes Feed The Pack
Eyes Up - Dodgers must be able to see past their own defenseman.
The Looks - As players dodges the looks will follow a simple progression of “Inside - Back Side - Ball Side”.
Quiet Stick - Dodgers must be able to distribute the ball at a moments notice. In order to do that, their stick can not be flailing around, it must be as close to a position where they can throw an accurate pass as possible.
Misdirection - Ball carriers can manipulate backside defenseman using their eyes. Look Back Fakes - Looking behind you to a teammate.
No Looks - Looking one direction and passing another.

The players in Group 2 will read the dodge and their defenseman to time up consecutive movements that generally create a “Scissor”, “X”, or “Criss Cross” formation. The two movements will be dictated by the direction the ball carrier dodges.

1st, the ball side player will move across the face of goal to the back pipe. If his defenseman slides, he will be open.

2nd, the backside player will move toward the ball in the wake of the first players movement. If his defenseman covers the 1st cut across the crease, he will be open. If a defenseman from the 3rd group tries to help the 1st or 2nd cut, it will open the skip lanes for our snipers.

The players in Group 3 will create space for the dodger by fading away from them while reading defenseman and trying to find skip lanes for the dodger to feed through. They will get open when their defenseman try to help on the crease, show toward the dodger, or ball watch and lose their men. When the ball is skipped through to them, they will look to take immediate step downs or dodge defenseman that are recovering through the defense.

The cornerstone of this offense is that all of the looks play off each other.

1 - If the dodger beats their man, he’ll score.

2.0 - If their ball side adjacent defenseman slides, our ball side sniper will be open.

2 .1 - If their ball side crease defenseman slides, our 1st cut will be open.

3.0 - If the 2nd slide covers the 1st cut, our 2nd cut will be open.

4.0 - If their 3rd slide covers our 2nd cut, our backside sniper will be open.

If nothing is there… move the ball… keep playing…

Watch the POWLAX Video for highlights when these prescribed looks weren’t there!

<!-- wp:html -->
<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/bmrk8QIyI3A?start=36&end=183&rel=0" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>
<!-- /wp:html -->

The most important aspect of this offense is the ability to beat the defenseman 1v1. If the dodgers cannot beat their men, this offense may not be the best for your team to use. When we are considering dodging, we would like to dodge the short sticks not the long sticks.

column2: Cuse - Draw and Attack the Backside
column3:
If the dodger draws a slide, they have the option of throwing backwards to the top so the ball can be swung to the opposite side for the second dodge or throwing the ball forwards for a dodge from x or swing to the backside fading player.

The best aspect of this offense is that the simplicity allows for players to know when and where the next dodge should become from.

Short Stick Placement: As we begin the offense, we’d like to dodge the short stick defenseman. We can even set them up so that we get 2 dodges vs short sticks in quick succession by making sure that the player being defended by the other short stick defenseman starts top center. That way, the initial motion will pull the second short stick defenseman to the backside, enabling us to quickly swing the ball and dodge the other short stick.

If the dodger sweeps across the top, he must try to turn the corner and score. If the defense slides from the crease player he will throw back to the player that mirrored from the crease to the wing behind him.

If they slide adjacent from the fading player who was top center, he will throw past the slide to the fading player who can dodge down the alley initiating a second motion.

If you would like your team to initiate using a two-man game, all of the rules stay exactly the same except for the player on the crease, who will move out for the 2 man game prior to the dodge. After the motions have been run, the spacing and locations will be the same.
This is an introduction to the Twist Man Up Play.

Welcome to POWLAX courses! There are two things I’d like to cover before we get started.

Print the Playbook PDF and Follow Along - Most lessons have a playbook PDF in the “Lesson Materials” section. Download, print, and follow along for the most complete experience.

Video Navigation - Most topics feature a YouTube video that will start and end at specific times that correspond to the current topic. You can navigate outside of these times, but once you do, the programmed end time will void and the video will not stop automatically.

Non-Linear Courses, Quizzes, and Completion - The majority of courses are non-linear, allowing you to skip ahead and go backward as you please. This allows you to take quizzes at anytime and can create an issue where specific topics may be skipped. If you skip a topic, you will need to go back can hit the “Mark as Complete” button to receive credit after testing out of the quiz.

column2: PBO - Pick Name and Definition Clarification
column3:
In the Penn State Picks Behind Offense video, I use incorrect names for a couple picking strategies. Below you will find the correct names and diagrams.


  1. Razor Pick - Patrick called the Razor Pick, an East West Pick in the video. A “Razor Pick” is a pick set on GLE where the ball carrier runs horizontally across the field as shown below. It is called a razor pick because it separates the ball carrier from the defenseman like a razor cutting through a piece of paper. Notice how M1’s pick forces D1 to separate and move over the top as A1 accelerates from back left through X to the right side of the field.

  2. Slam Pick - Patrick called the Slam Pick a Razor Pick in the video. A “Slam Pick” is a pick set on GLE where the ball carrier is running vertically, rounding the crease to get above GLE. Notice how M1 sets a pick as A1 is trying to round the crease and get upfield.

This video covers a correction to how we communicate the formations within the 21-12 offense so that motions from the Attack and Midfield group would share the same number. I want you to see this before the original way so that it will be fresh in your mind as you watch the rest of the video.

column2: 43A - 4-3 Alpha vs Lock All Except Goalie.
column3:
<!-- wp:html -->
<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/4LOocXTxHNw?start=1059&end=1285&rel=0" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>
<!-- /wp:html -->

The section of the video below is from the 2-3-2 Clear video and it shows another way we can think about moving up field and subbing within our 4-3 Clear. If we want to substitute 2 players as we clear instead of just 1, we can have the midfielders take both off box positions and substitute two defensive players for the first two players on the next midfield line.

Instead of having the two midfielders cross the midline and set up on the left and right hashes, only one will cross and he will line up on the off box hash. The other will replace the defenseman who is on the off box midline and he will stay on sides, potentially being our alpha. The defenseman who would have gone to the off box side midline, will now be free to sub off the field for our second sub, who will sub on on sides. The defenseman standing at the face off X in the 2-3-2 clear will be the third player in the base of our 4-3 clear.

This is an advanced subbing pattern, but it can definitely help with getting substitutions done faster.

With the addition of the “Over and Back” rule, our Attackman no longer want to begin at the midline when the ball is on the defensive side of the field. If they stay below the restraining line and their defenseman guards them close, we will gain position on all errant passes that cross the midline. The only reason the Attackman should be at the midline is if their defenseman moves up to make a play on a ball rolling to the midline. In the event a defenseman is trying to hit an errant pass back to their offense, our attack should box out and lift the defenders stick. This will ensure that the ball crosses the midline, giving us the ball.

With the addition of the Over and Back rule, defensively, we would like to be closer to the midline than our Attackman. This will allow us to get to the midline to hit any errant passes back to our offense.

Description: This practice focuses on fundamental midfield skills including cradling, stick protection, passing, and shooting split techniques.

Location of Drills: Anywhere, Behind The Goal, Around the Goal, Wing Right or Left.

Equipment Needed: Balls, Goal, Cones, Bounce Back or Partner, Speed Ladder.

Equipment Needed: Balls, Goal, Cones, Bounce Back or Partner, Speed Ladder.
